The mention oi the responsa pmdentium among the sources oi the ius civile makes it necessary to speak of the work done by the jurist class in the development oi Roman law; and as it was to the jurists that that law owed what scientific form it possessed, besides many oi its other special ments, it will not be amiss to discuss this subject with some sullness. The names oi the early prudentes who lived under the free Republic are collected by Pomponius in Dig. 1· a. 2. 35-39 ; the first is that of Papirius, whose compilationes the leges regiae hasbeen already noticed. These earliest lawyers are styled prudentes not because their knowledge oi the law was more scientific, less empirical, than that oi other men, but rather because they knew it more fully; a philosophical treatment of law had not yet commenced and such distinction as there was between their legal knowledge and that os the ordinary citizen was quantitative rather than qualitative. The first condition of their existence as a professional class was the ces- sation oi the pontifices to be ‘iuris conditores,’ and the liberation of pri· vate law lrom the setters oi the ius sacrum3 it has been suggested that this was affected in the main by the incorporation oi the plebeian element in the state. The direction oi their legal activity is denoted by Cicero (de Orat. i. 48) by the four ternis respondere, cavere, agere, and scribere.
